      <bioghist id="aspace_c23aa0cf65b547ba7a68c1a27f9d9ca3">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Edward N. DeWitt (1887-1983) was an ophthalmologist and educator who spent his career working in Connecticut. He was the fourth ophthalmologist to be board certified in the State of Connecticut. DeWitt was born in Hastings, Minnesota, attended Harvard as an undergraduate, and completed his MD at the University of Pennsylvania Medical College in 1917. He worked as a senior surgical intern at Bridgeport Hospital before serving in the US Army Medical Corps in World War I. After the war he entered practice as an ophthalmologist and otologist with Doctor Dorlan Smith in Bridgeport. He was a clinical instructor in ocular pathology from 1931-1936, then assistant clinical professor  from 1936-1942 at the Yale University Medical School. He was chief of the Department of Ophthalmology at Bridgeport Hospital from 1948 to 1953 and was a consulting ophthalmologist at St. Vincent's Hospital and Fairfield Hills Hospital, Newtown.</p>
         <p>During his career, DeWitt was a fellow of the American Academy of Ophthalmology and Otolaryngology and the American College of Surgeons; a member of the Association of Research in Ophthalmology, the Bridgeport Medical Society, the Connecticut Medical Society, the Connecticut State Committee for the Blind, the Fairfield County Medical Society, and the Pan-American Association of Ophthalmology; and a Diplomate of the American Board of Ophthalmology.</p>
         <p>source: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1312435/</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_043564e7af25c95da29362101103c454">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
